{{Infobox book | name = Rewire | image = Rewire Digital Cosmopolitans in the Age of Connection.jpg | image_size = 200 | caption = | author = [[Ethan Zuckerman]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = USA | language = English | series = | subject = [[Globalization]] | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | publisher = [[W. W. Norton & Company]] | pub_date = June 17, 2013 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 312 pp. | isbn = 978-0393082838 | oclc = 811599512 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Rewire: Digital Cosmopolitans in the Age of Connection''''' is a 2013 nonfiction [[book]] about contemporary [[globalization]] and [[xenophilia]] by American blogger [[Ethan Zuckerman]] of [[MIT]]. It describes [[homophily|homophilic]] barriers to [[cosmopolitanism]] such as [[filter bubble]]s and [[media bias]]. Zuckerman calls for a strenuously internationalized [[Media literacy|media]] and [[Cultural literacy|cultural]] literacy empowered by [[language translation]]. He cites the work of scholars [[Kwame Anthony Appiah]], [[Ronald Stuart Burt]], [[Mark Granovetter]], and [[Robert D. Putnam]], and of cosmopolitan exemplars [[Matt Harding]], [[Erik Hersman]], [[Dhani Tackles the Globe|Dhani Jones]], [[EastSouthWestNorth|Roland Soong]], [[Global Voices Online]], [http://www.harnu.com Härnu], [[Meedan]], and [http://www.tealeafnation.com Tea Leaf Nation].<ref>{{Cite book |publisher = W.W. Norton & Company |isbn = 9780393082838 |title = Rewire |url = https://openlibrary.org/books/OL25428329M/Rewire |author = Ethan Zuckerman |publication-date = 2013 }}</ref>
